TO RUN THE CODE:
    1. Unzip folder
    2. Go to the Nand2Tetris Online IDE
    3. Navigate to the Jack Compiler
    4. Select open a folder
    5. Open the folder in the Jack Compiler
    6. Press "compile" and "run"
    7. After being automatically brought to the VM Emulator, set the run speed to the fastest setting
    8. Press enable keyboard, and run


CONTROLS: 
    W/A/S/D - player movement
    ESC - exit the program


CLASS OVERVIEW:
    Main:
        - main class, runs and closes the program.

    Game:
        - Game object, creates, updates, and facilitates data transfers between all other classes.
        - Creates a doubly linked list of Room nodes, then draws the root room.
         -If all Gift objects are delivered to all NPCs (tracked by int counter), update root and bedroom Room layouts.
        - Recieves inputs from keyboard. (recieveInput())
        - Moves player character in the direction input (runInput()).
        - If movement is not possible, checks sprite collisions, room loading, and NPC/Gift interactions.

    Player:
        - Player character object.
        - Contains coordinates (top_left corner), hasGift and drawBlack booleans, and sprite drawing instructions.
        - Movement methods return a "move code" (-1=teleport, 1-collided, 0=move normally).
        - If teleport is returned, Game class loades next/previous room in the list.
        - if collided, player doesn't move, and Game checks for NPC/Gift interactions.

    Room:
        - Doubly linked list node object class.
        - contains references to the previous and next element in the list, as well as number coded room layouts, array of Prop objects,
          and NPC and Gift objects.
        - contains NPC and Gift boundary coordinates. Contained here instead of NPC and Gift classes respectively for faster completion
          time.

    NPC:
        - NPC object class.
        - Contains coordinates (top left), a single boolean recievedGift, and draw instructions.
        - recievedGift is updated to be true when the Player's hasGift boolean is also true, and collides (or interacts) with it.

    Gift:
        - Gift object class.
        - Contains coordinates (top left), a single boolean collected, and draw instructions.
        - collected is updated to be true when the Player's hasGift boolean is false, and collides (or interacts) with it.
        - when collected, the sprite is erased permanently.

    Prop:
        - Simple object class that contains number coded prop types, coordinates, and draw instructions for each prop type.

WARNING WHEN LOOKING AT CODE:
        While the code is commented to be as clear as it can be, it is still somewhat messy and confusing. This is primarily
    an issue with the methods handling movement. Since this program was built on top of the Square demo program provided by Nand2Tetris,
    the movement logic is a heavily expanded version of the movement system in the demo, and may not be the most optimal system for
    a program with this much complexity (each and every movement checks for next/previous room loading, then collisions, and then
    for normal movement instead of attempting to move normally first, then checking for the other scenarios if normal movement is not
    possible). There are also magic numbers, which are especially prevalent in Gift, NPC, Room, and Prop drawing instructions. This
    was done for quicker development time, but does lead to more confusing code.

KNOWN ISSUES:
    1. When exiting the program, the program does not dispose every class. 
        For the ones it does dispose, it does not dispose them correctly.
    2. The player's eyes can still be seen in the secret ending screen, as the player is still drawn in their inverted colors.
    3. Interactions with NPCs when approached from the left do not work. Gift states are not updated when the player has a gift.
    4. The player may clip into and erase portions of the room walls when loading a new room when holding towards the wall.


FUTURE PLANS:
    Highest priority:
        1. Fix all known bugs.
        2. Clarify magic numbers
        3. Restructure movement code to be more efficent, and less messily connected.
    
    Lower priority:
        1. Player idle and walking animations.
        2. Secret monster and NPC idle animations.
        3. More detailed sprites, as well as more efficient drawing instructions for many of the props.
        4. NPC dialogue. 
    